#week-title("Two", "Saturn & Jupiter Hours for Mineral Operations")

=== Core Teaching

At the daily level, planetary hours continue to govern the beginning of
operations. In the mineral work, the choice of planetary hour carries more
weight than in the vegetable work because the mineral preparation will carry
whatever force is present at its initiation for far longer.

*Saturn hours for antimony and lead work.* The Saturday and Saturn hours are
the natural time for beginning operations with stibnite and lead. Saturn's
qualities — restriction, patience, crystallisation, time — align with the
nature of these minerals. The calcination of stibnite (driving off the Sulphur
and reducing to oxide) is particularly suited to Saturday in the hour of Saturn.

*Jupiter hours for multiplication and expansion.* When a preparation has
reached a stage where it is being multiplied — where fresh essence is being
added to an already-elevated salt, or where the preparation is being extended
through further cohobation cycles — the Jupiter hour (and Thursday) supports
this expansive movement. Jupiter's quality of generosity and multiplication
directly assists preparations in their growth phase.

*Solar hours for gold-related and Tiphereth-level work.* Any operation
connected with the Sun sphere — including the contemplation of the goal of
the Work, the creation of tinctures intended to work on the heart and
vital forces, and work with gold itself — aligns with Sunday and solar hours.
In practice, the review of all active preparations is naturally suited to
Sunday in the solar hour: bringing the solar consciousness of Tiphereth to
bear on the full range of the Work.

*Mercury hours for precise observation and record-keeping.* Laboratory
record-keeping, analysis of results, and the writing of the laboratory journal
are Mercurial activities. Wednesday in the hour of Mercury is the natural time
for documentation sessions and the critical review of observations.

=== Topics This Week

- Saturn hours and days for antimony and lead operations
- Jupiter hours for multiplication and cohobation cycles
- Solar hours for gold work and Tiphereth-level review
- Mercury hours for documentation and analytical review

#inner-work[
  *Integrating Timing into Daily Practice*

  Begin this week to elect the planetary hour for every significant laboratory
  action — not just major beginnings but the weekly observations, the
  cohobation cycles, the documentation sessions.

  Record the elected hour alongside each lab entry. After one week, review:
  does electing the hour change the quality of attention you bring to the
  session? Even if the effect is subtle, it is real.
]

